&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept-&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The earth acts like a magnet.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;magnetic field of earth&lt;/strong&gt; is generated due to the&amp;nbsp;electric currents&amp;nbsp;produced by the motion of&amp;nbsp;convection currents&amp;nbsp;of molten iron in the&amp;nbsp;Earth&amp;#39;s outer core.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;earth&amp;rsquo;s magnetic field changes when we move from one place to another&lt;/strong&gt; on the earth&amp;rsquo;s surface.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When a rod is moving in a &lt;strong&gt;magnetic field&lt;/strong&gt; then an &lt;strong&gt;emf is generated across its ends&lt;/strong&gt;. The emf is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Emf generated&lt;/strong&gt; = B V l&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where B is magnetic field perpendicular to the velocity of rod, V is velocity of rod and l I is length of the rod.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;vertical component of magnetic field (B&lt;sub&gt;V&lt;/sub&gt;)&lt;/strong&gt; of earth is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;B&lt;sub&gt;V&lt;/sub&gt; = B Sin&amp;theta;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where B is earth&amp;rsquo;s magnetic field at a point, and &amp;theta; is angle of dip&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation-&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given that:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Length of the wing (l) = 20 m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Angle of dip (&amp;theta;) = 30&amp;deg;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Earth&amp;rsquo;s magnetic field (B) = 4 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;-4&lt;/sup&gt; T&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Velocity (V) = 400 m/s&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;B&lt;sub&gt;V&lt;/sub&gt; = B Sin&amp;theta; = 4 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;-4&lt;/sup&gt; T Sin30&amp;deg; = 4 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;-4&lt;/sup&gt; T &amp;times; &amp;frac12; = 2 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;-4&lt;/sup&gt; T&lt;/p&gt;
Emf generated = B&lt;sub&gt;V&lt;/sub&gt; V l = 2 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;-4&lt;/sup&gt; T &amp;times; 400 &amp;times; 20 = 1.6 Volt

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept-&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;radius of the path&lt;/strong&gt; followed by a charge particle in &lt;strong&gt;magnetic field&lt;/strong&gt; is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(r = \;\frac{{mV}}{{q\;B}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where m is mass of charge particle, V is velocity of charge particle, q is charge and B is magnetic field in which charge particle is moving&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Kinetic energy&lt;/strong&gt; of charge particle in a magnetic field is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(KE = \frac{{{B^2}{q^2}{r^2}}}{{2\;m}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(Radius\;\left( r \right) = \sqrt {\frac{{2\;m\;KE}}{{{B^2}{q^2}}}} = \frac{{\sqrt m }}{{\;q}}\left( {\;\frac{{\sqrt {2\;KE} }}{B}} \right)\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where B is magnetic field, q is charge, r is radius and m is mass of the charge particle&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation-&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let mass of a proton (m&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt;) = m and charge on a proton (q&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt;) = e&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Mass of deuteron (m&lt;sub&gt;d&lt;/sub&gt;) = 2 &amp;times; mass of a proton = 2 m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Charge on deuteron (q&lt;sub&gt;d&lt;/sub&gt;) = charge on a proton = e&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Mass of an alpha particle (m&lt;sub&gt;&amp;alpha;&lt;/sub&gt;) = 4 &amp;times; mass of a proton = 4 m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Charge on an alpha particle (q&lt;sub&gt;&amp;alpha;&lt;/sub&gt;) = 2 &amp;times; charge on a proton = 2 e&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;All three particles have same kinetic energy (KE)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(Radius\;of\;proton\;\left( {{r_p}} \right) = \frac{{\sqrt m }}{{\;q}}\left( {\;\frac{{\sqrt {2\;KE} }}{B}} \right) = \frac{{\sqrt m }}{{\;e}}\left( {\;\frac{{\sqrt {2\;KE} }}{B}} \right) = r\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(Radius\;of\;deuteron\;\left( {{r_d}} \right) = \frac{{\sqrt {{m_d}} }}{{\;{q_d}}}\left( {\;\frac{{\sqrt {2\;KE} }}{B}} \right) = \frac{{\sqrt {\;2\;m} }}{{\;e}}\left( {\;\frac{{\sqrt {2\;KE} }}{B}} \right) = \sqrt {2\;} r\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(Radius\;of\;alpha\;\left( {{r_\alpha }} \right) = \frac{{\sqrt {{m_\alpha }} }}{{\;{q_\alpha }}}\left( {\;\frac{{\sqrt {2\;KE} }}{B}} \right) = \frac{{\sqrt {\;4\;m} }}{{\;\;2\;e}}\left( {\;\frac{{\sqrt {2\;KE} }}{B}} \right) = r\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
Ratio = r&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt; : r&lt;sub&gt;d&lt;/sub&gt; : r&lt;sub&gt;&amp;alpha; &lt;/sub&gt;= r : &amp;radic;2 r : r = 1 : &amp;radic;2 : 1

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:.25in;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The magnetic inclination or Angle of dip:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;angle&lt;/strong&gt; made by the earth&amp;rsquo;s &lt;strong&gt;total magnetic field&lt;/strong&gt;, B with the horizontal direction in the magnetic meridian is called as the magnetic inclination at that place&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is the &lt;strong&gt;angle&lt;/strong&gt; by which the &lt;strong&gt;total intensity of the earth&amp;rsquo;s magnetic field dips&lt;/strong&gt; or comes out of the horizontal plane; It is different at different places and measured using a &amp;ldquo;Dip Circle&amp;rdquo;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;At the magnetic equator, the dip needle rests horizontally at an angle of zero degrees while, at the magnetic poles, the magnetic needle rests vertically, at an angle of 90 degrees.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;At all the other places, the angle of dip is between 0 and 90 degrees.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Since as explained above &lt;strong&gt;Angle of dip&lt;/strong&gt; is the angle between the earth&amp;#39;s resultant magnetic field from horizontal.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;And angular Dip is &lt;strong&gt;zero at equator&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;positive&lt;/strong&gt; in the &lt;strong&gt;northern hemisphere&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Whereas in &lt;strong&gt;southern hemispheredip angle&lt;/strong&gt; is considered as &lt;strong&gt;negative&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence if A is located in the northern hemisphere and B is located in the southern hemisphere&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;delta; for A will be positive and negative for B&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Magnetic field: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The space or region around the &lt;strong&gt;current carrying&lt;/strong&gt; wire/&lt;strong&gt;moving electric charge&lt;/strong&gt; or around the magnetic material in which &lt;strong&gt;force of magnetism&lt;/strong&gt; can be experienced by other magnetic material is called as &lt;strong&gt;magnetic field/magnetic induction &lt;/strong&gt;by that material/current.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is denoted by B.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Force on a current carrying wire is given by;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;F = I(L &amp;times; B) = ILB Sin&amp;theta;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where L &amp;times; B is the cross product of length vector and the magnetic field vector, &amp;theta; is the angle between wire and the magnetic field and I is current in the wire.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given that:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Current = I = 2 A&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Magnetic field = B = 24 Tesla&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Angle = &amp;theta; = 30&amp;deg;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Length = L = 3m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Force on wire = ILB sin&amp;theta; = 2 &amp;times; 3 &amp;times; 24 Sin (30&amp;deg;)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(F = 2 \times 6 \times 24 \times \frac{1}{2} = 72\;N\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If the circular loop is considered as a magnetic dipole, then the dipole moment is the product of current and area. But the circular loop has multiple numbers of turns.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the &lt;strong&gt;magnitude of dipole moment = area &amp;times; current &amp;times; number of turns.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;i.e. M = NIA&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where, Magnetic moment of copper coil = M&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;No of loops = N&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Current flowing though loop = I&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Area of coil = r&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Current flowing in a loop = 6 A&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Radius of loop = 2 cm = 0.02 m&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Number of turns = 50&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore magnetic moment for a copper coil can be given as,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(M) = N&amp;times; I&amp;times; (&amp;pi;r&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;M = 50 &amp;times; 6 &amp;times;&amp;pi; &amp;times; (0.02)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;there4; M = 0.37 Am&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
